Protest Domain Report: Drug trade

Row

This dashboard summarizes deaths in the Drug trade protest domain in the Ultimate Consequences database. All deaths in the dataset are categorized into a general arena of conflict, each of which may involve multiple events and campaigns.

Overall, the database catalogs deaths in Bolivian political conflict during the democratic era, 10 October 1982 to the present. The map to the right shows these deaths broken down by municipality. Politically and administratively, the country is divided into 9 departments, 112 provinces, 340 municipalities and 1,384 cantons.

There have been 5 deadly events involving 10 confirmed deaths and a total of 11 listed deaths in the Drug trade domain of protest.

  • Deaths in this domain comprise 2% of all confirmed deaths.
  • Drug trade ranks 12 out of 20 domains in the dataset.
  • There were 7 killed by state security forces, and there were 1 state-affiliated victims.
  • The average age of the deceased in this domain is 38.33 years. The youngest was 19 years old and the oldest was 62 years old.

The table below can be ordered by any of its variables and searched by the text variables as well as the year. At the bottom you can choose how many events to show, or page through the events. By default, events are ordered chronologically.
